1st Modeling part: predicting ratio of choosing a broker/ who is going to choose a broker:

Test and train split:

set.seed(512)
train_indices <- createDataPartition(y = data$broker_yes_no,
                                     times = 1,
                                     p = 0.8,
                                     list = FALSE)
data_train <- data[train_indices, ]
data_test <- data[-train_indices, ]

Lasso:

lasso <- train(broker_yes_no ~
                 segment +
                 how_independent +
                 trading_exp +
                 how_much_money +
                 how_often +
                 market +
                 simple_prod +
                 sophisticated +
                 leveraged +
                 fx +
                 investor_protection,
               intercept = FALSE,
               method = "glmnet",
               metric = "ROC",
               data = data_train,
               trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",
                                        number = 5,
                                        classProbs = TRUE,
                                        summaryFunction=twoClassSummary,
                                        selectionFunction = "oneSE"),
               tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha=1,
                                      lambda=c(0.001,
                                               0.002,
                                               0.003,
                                               0.004,
                                               0.005,
                                               0.01,
                                               0.02,
                                               0.03,
                                               0.035,
                                               0.04,
                                               0.045,
                                               0.05)))

Predicting on the test set:

data_test$lasso_pred <- predict.train(lasso, newdata = data_test)

threshold <- 0.3
data_test[, lasso_pred:= ifelse(lasso_pred_prob > threshold, "yes", "no")]

Decision Tree:

train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv",
                              number = 5,
                              classProbs = TRUE,
                              selectionFunction = "oneSE",
                              summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)
tree_model <- train(broker_yes_no ~ segment + how_independent + trading_exp + how_much_money + how_often + market + simple_prod + sophisticated + leveraged + fx + investor_protection,
                    method = "rpart",
                    data = data_train,
                    tuneGrid = data.frame("cp" = c(0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1)),
                    trControl = train_control,
                    metric = "ROC")

Before running our model. We then choose the level of our outcome that we wish to use as our baseline and specify this in the relevel function. Then, we run our model using multinom. The multinom package does not include p-value calculation for the regression coefficients, so we calculate p-values using Wald tests (here z-tests).

data_one_hot$broker <- relevel(data_one_hot$broker, ref = "degiro")

The ratio of the probability of choosing one outcome category over the probability of choosing the baseline category is often referred as relative risk (and it is also sometimes referred as odds as we have just used to described the regression parameters above). The relative risk is the right-hand side linear equation exponentiated, leading to the fact that the exponentiated regression coefficients are relative risk ratios for a unit change in the predictor variable. We can exponentiate the coefficients from our model to see these risk ratios.
